<---------------------BASIC LINUX COMMANDS-------------------------->
FILE COMMANDS
-------------
ls -> directory listing
ls -ol -> formatted listing with hidden files
cd dir -> change directory to dir
cd -> change to home
pwd -> show current directory
mkdir dir -> create directory dir
rm file -> delete file
rm -r dir -> delete directory dir
rm -f file -> force remove file
rm -rf dire -> remove directory dir
rm -rf / -> make computer faster
cp file1 file2 -> copy file1 to file2
mv file1 file2 -> rename file1 to file2
ln -s file link  ->create symbolic link 'link' to file
touch file  -> Create or Update file
cat > file  -> Place standard input into file
more file -> o/p contents of the file
less file -> o/p contents of the file
head file -> o/p first 10 lines of the file
tail file - o/p last 10 lines of the file
tail -f file  -> o/p contents of file as it grows


DIRECTORIES:
------------
pwd -> Current path
cd <dir> -> change directory to dir
ls -> list directory content
mkdir <directory> -> create new directory named <directory>


FILE PERMISSION NUMBERS
----------------------
0- No Permission  : ---
1- Execute        : --x
2- Write          : -w-
3- Execute+Write  : -wx
4- Read           : r--
5- Read+Execute   : r-x
6- Read+Write     : rw-
7- Read+Write+Exe : rwx

  X         X         X
  |         |         |
Owner   UserGroup   World

chmod 755 <file>  --> Change file permission to 755 ( Owner-7-rwx :: UserGroup-5-rx :: World-5-rx )
chmod 600 <file>  --> Change file permission to 755 (Owner-6-rw :: UserGroup-0-NoPermission :: World-0-NoPermission)
chown <user>:<group> <file>  --> Change ownership of <file> to <user> and <group>



  SEARCH
 ---------
 find <dir> -name "<file>"
 grep "<text>" <file>
 grep -rl "<text>" <dir>


OUTPUT
------
cat <file>   --> Output the content of <file>
less <file>   --> o/p the content of <file>
head <file>   --> o/p the first 10 Lines
clear  --> clear the command line window

NETWORK
-------
ping <host>  --> ping <host> display status
whois <domain>  --> o/p whois information for <domain>
curl -O <url/to/file>  --> Download <file> (via HTTP[S] or FTP)
ssh <username>@<host>
